SIMPLE: meteoric
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Meteoric
<hw>Me`te*or"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>m⟦eacute⟧t⟦eacute⟧orique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or
pertaining to a meteor, or to meteors; atmospheric, <as>as,
<ex>meteoric</ex> phenomena; <ex>meteoric</ex> stones.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Influenced by the weather; <as>as, <ex>meteoric</ex>
conditions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Flashing; transient and brilliant, like a meteor{3};
<as>as, <ex>meteoric</ex> fame</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Meteoric</xex>
politician.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Craik.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Meteoric iron</b></col>, <col><b>Meteoric
stone</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Min.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Meteorite</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Meteoric paper</b></col>, <cd>a
substance of confervoid origin found floating in the air, and resembling
bits of coarse paper; -- so called because formerly supposed to fall
from meteors.</cd> -- <col><b>Meteoric showers</b></col>, <cd>periodical
exhibitions of shooting stars, occuring about the 9th or 10th of August
and 13th of November, more rarely in April and December, and also at
some other periods.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meteorical</ent>⟦br⟧
